{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/immunizations-seasonal-influenza/background-information/definition-of-influenza/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"2ecf8cae-934e-53ec-8216-de939261798a","slug":"definition-of-influenza","fullItemName":"Definition of influenza","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 5530ff04-1b62-4120-81c7-6ed949de5515 --><h2>What is influenza?</h2><!-- end field 5530ff04-1b62-4120-81c7-6ed949de5515 -->","summary":"","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 1a30f64d-8804-461c-8dea-dddea5950148 --><!-- begin field 317aa6a8-2a52-4f38-b2a1-c0a53ae9a604 --><ul><li>Influenza is an acute viral infection of the respiratory tract. Influenza types A and B are responsible for most cases of clinical illness in the UK.<ul><li>In healthy people, seasonal influenza is usually a self-limiting condition, and recovery is typically within 2–7 days.</li><li>In older people and those in specific <a class=\"topic-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/immunizations-seasonal-influenza/management/immunizations-seasonal-influenza/#who-to-immunize\">clinical risk groups</a>, seasonal influenza may be more likely to result in serious complications such as pneumonia, meningitis, encephalitis, and death.</li><li>For further information on the symptoms, complications, and management of seasonal influenza, see the CKS topic on <a class=\"topic-reference external-reference\" href=\"/topics/influenza-seasonal/\">Influenza - seasonal</a>.</li></ul></li></ul><p>[<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/immunizations-seasonal-influenza/references/\">PHE, 2019a</a>]</p><!-- end field 317aa6a8-2a52-4f38-b2a1-c0a53ae9a604 --><!-- end item 1a30f64d-8804-461c-8dea-dddea5950148 -->","topic":{"id":"9b6b800a-723f-5d15-a3b3-e02063fe3c99","topicId":"92586dea-3104-4e8a-bc44-03b987a2edbd","topicName":"Immunizations - seasonal influenza","slug":"immunizations-seasonal-influenza","lastRevi